@@yThe Arroyo@@N

  A @@ejurisdictional wound in stone@@N where a river became a court. Long
before desert routes hardened into law, the Arroyo was a branch of
the Iseth watershed's seasonal spill system, carrying violent flood-
water and silt from western uplands. When drought intensified and
river governance shifted to cistern law, this channel was engineered,
taxed, abandoned, and repurposed.

  The critical transformation was institutional. The Arroyo became a
place where @@ywater volume was translated into legal obligation@@N.
Travelers crossing were measured, assessed, and recorded. Debts were
written against drought. Oaths were notarized against thirst.

  Five historical layers remain active simultaneously. @@eKeeper Era@@N
survey engineers established marker yards, flood gauges, and wayline
obelisks. They introduced @@ythirst oaths@@N -- emergency water draws in
exchange for deferred service -- and witness stones recording both
route distance and owed allocation. In Keeper doctrine, the Arroyo
was a legal instrument, not terrain.

  The @@ySalt Ledger Kingdoms@@N weaponized these systems. Assessors in
fortified cutbank courts suspended legal identity until debt was paid.
Dead travelers whose funerary rites were withheld pending settlement
became @@d"unpaid names"@@N -- a phrase that still carries weight in the
canyon's dry corridors.

  @@dPyramid influence@@N moved funerary doctrine into administration.
Moon-descending legal language reframed debt default as spiritual
trespass. Inscriptions combined route law with burial entitlement.
Northern Pyramid preservation rhetoric responded, creating a textual
palimpsest: Keeper numerics under Ledger seals, Ledger seals under
Moon clauses, Moon clauses crossed by late preservation annotations.

  After corridor institutions broke, @@rJackal-derived synod offshoots@@N
simplified complex formulas into coercive toll liturgy. "Authorized
thirst" became both prayer and threat. Brood colonies expanded into
unattended mortuary sectors, embedding chitin and resin in old record
halls. Undead manifestations cluster where oath, debt, and burial
records conflict -- not random hauntings but unresolved legal-memory
loops anchored to inscription sites.

  Today the @@rCharter Reclaimers@@N run extortion checkpoints with copied
charter rods. @@dDustbound Court-Dead@@N reenact fragments of procedure,
demanding declarations and marking defaults. The @@rResin Matriarch's@@N
brood nests through warm ossuary rubble. And in the deepest fault
galleries, @@dfault manifestations@@N rise from meridian-scar fractures
as dust vortices with voice-like harmonics.

  The Arroyo is what happens when five competing control systems
persist in one canyon, and none can establish uncontested legitimacy.
